<bdy>

<b>Walkscore.com</b> is the first large-scale, public access <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../361/12031361.xml">
walkability</link> index. According to the <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../226/102226.xml">
Washington Post</link></it>, "Walkscore.com ranks communities nationwide (and soon, globally) based on how many businesses, parks, theaters, schools and other common destinations are within walking distance of any given starting point."<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref> 
<sec>
<st>
Algorithm</st>
<p>

According to the site's creators, 
<indent level="1">

"The Walk Score algorithm awards points based on the distance to the closest amenity in each category. If the closest amenity in a category is within .25 miles (or .4 km), we assign the maximum number of points. The number of points declines as the distance approaches 1 mile (or 1.6 km)—no points are awarded for amenities further than 1 mile. Each category is weighted equally and the points are summed and normalized to yield a score from 0–100. The number of nearby amenities is the leading predictor of whether people walk."<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref>
</indent>

</p>
